## 6. Performance Diagnostics with Frame Timing and FPS Tracking

The renderer now tracks performance metrics in real-time, providing visibility into frame
times and rendering bottlenecks.

### Performance Statistics

Performance stats track frame timing with a rolling window:

```rust
struct PerfStats {
    frame_times: VecDeque<f32>,
    capacity: usize,
    frame_start: Option<Instant>,
}

impl PerfStats {
    fn new(capacity: usize) -> Self {
        Self {
            frame_times: VecDeque::with_capacity(capacity),
            capacity,
            frame_start: None,
        }
    }

    fn begin_frame(&mut self) {
        self.frame_start = Some(Instant::now());
    }

    fn end_frame(&mut self) -> PerfSnapshot {
        let elapsed = self.frame_start
            .map(|start| start.elapsed().as_secs_f32() * 1000.0)
            .unwrap_or(0.0);

        self.frame_times.push_back(elapsed);
        if self.frame_times.len() > self.capacity {
            self.frame_times.pop_front();
        }

        self.snapshot(elapsed)
    }

    fn snapshot(&self, latest: f32) -> PerfSnapshot {
        let sum: f32 = self.frame_times.iter().sum();
        let avg = if !self.frame_times.is_empty() {
            sum / self.frame_times.len() as f32
        } else {
            latest
        };

        let min = self.frame_times.iter().copied().fold(f32::INFINITY, f32::min);
        let max = self.frame_times.iter().copied().fold(f32::NEG_INFINITY, f32::max);

        PerfSnapshot {
            latest_ms: latest,
            average_ms: avg,
            min_ms: min,
            max_ms: max,
            fps: if avg > 0.0 { 1000.0 / avg } else { 0.0 },
        }
    }
}
```

The rolling window (default 240 frames = 4 seconds) smooths out transient spikes while
remaining responsive to sustained changes.

